'''Sendai Naked Pilgrimage''' (仙台裸参り, Sendai Hadaka-mairi) is a traditional event held in [[:en:Sendai|Sendai]], [[:en:Miyagi Prefecture|Miyagi Prefecture]]. Taking place during the coldest time of the year (around January), participants dressed in loincloths, sandals, and other minimal clothing walk to shrines to pray. Closely associated with the {{ill|Matsutaki Festival|ja|松焚祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Matsutaki Festival|qq=}} at Ōsaki Hachiman Shrine and the {{ill|Donto Festival|ja|どんと祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Donto Festival|qq=}} celebrated throughout Miyagi, it has spread to other areas in the prefecture.

The origins of the pilgrimage are linked to {{ill|Nambu Tōji|ja|南部杜氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nambu Tōji|qq=}}, traditional sake brewers (explained below). Over time, participants have expanded beyond brewers to include citizens, employees of companies, universities, hospitals, teachers, care workers, and various organizations. Participation peaked in 1992 with 200 groups and 7,500 participants but has since stabilized at around 100 groups and 3,000 participants annually. In 2021, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, participation at Ōsaki Hachiman Shrine’s Matsutaki Festival dropped to 50 groups and 368 participants, with some areas canceling the event entirely.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mainichi.jp/articles/20210114/k00/00m/040/288000c|title=コロナ終息願い「どんと祭」　「裸参り」参加者は激減　仙台・大崎八幡宮|newspaper=[[Mainichi Shimbun]]|date=2021-01-15|accessdate=2021-01-23}}</ref>

